The XPS spectra (Fig. 7
                     ) were used to analyze the surface elemental composition of the samples obtained in He and H2. These spectra contain two characteristic peaks: a C 1s (carbon) peak at 284.9 eV, and an O 1 s (oxygen) peak at 532.6 eV. The lack of an iron peak (720 eV) in the XPS spectra indicates that a negligible number of metal nanoparticles were eroded from the stainless steel electrode using this procedure. Since the products were synthesized in the absenceof oxygen, the existence of oxygen was ascribed to oxidation by H2O/O2 species when the products were exposed to ambient air. The high-resolution C 1s XPS spectra are also exhibited in Fig. 7, and each peak was deconvoluted into several peaks in Origin software. Three peaks were located at 284.5, 285.4, and 286.7 eV, which were assigned to sp2 carbons, sp3 carbons, and C-O functional groups, respectively (Tatarova et al., 2014). Table 4
                      lists the contents of each element in the products formed in He and H2. The carbon content was more than 98.8%, while the oxygen content was less than 1.2%, indicating a very high carbon content in the products. When the buffer gas changed from He to H2, the relative distribution of sp2 carbon increased from 84.3% to 87.1%, and the sp3 carbon content decreased from 12.1% to 10.6%, which indicated that the products obtained in H2 had a more crystalline structure, corroborating the TEM images and Raman spectra.
